                <head>317. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>The Ministerial Council of the Baghdad Pact held its fifth meeting in London,
                    July 27–28. On July 28, the Council issued a joint declaration in which the
                    United States agreed to cooperate with the Baghdad Pact members in ensuring
                    their defense and security against direct or indirect aggression. For text of
                    the declaration, signed by Prime Ministers <persName corresp="#p_NMFK1"
                        >Noon</persName> of Pakistan, Manouchehr Eghbal of Iran, Adnan Menderes <pb
                        facs="0691" n="659" xml:id="pg_659"/> of Turkey, and Harold Macmillan of the
                    United Kingdom as well as Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DAW1"
                        >Dulles</persName>, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>,
                    August 18, 1958, pages 272–273.</p>
                <p>Pursuant to the London Declaration, the United States began the negotiation of
                    bilateral defense agreements with Pakistan, Iran, and Turkey. Extensive
                    documentation on this subject is scheduled for publication in <ref
                        target="frus1958-60v12">volume XII</ref>. Documentation on the negotiations
                    with Pakistan are in Department of State, Central File 790D.5. See also <ref
                        target="#d341">Documents 341</ref> and <ref target="#d346">346</ref>.</p>
            </div>
